a. The Municipal Accountant shall regularly conduct monthly reconciliation of the Cash in Bank records for all of its bank accounts (whether local or foreign) with the depository bank balances within ten days from receipt of the bank statements and at least quarterly reconciliation with Municipal Treasurer’s cashbooks (including the Cash in Bank accounts), in compliance with Section 74 of PD 1445 and Section 181(c) of GAAM Volume 1. We recommended that the Management submit the BRS on time with complete supporting documents to the concerned COA auditor for verification;
b. The Municipal Treasurer shall submit and furnish to the Accountant all paid DVs summarized in the Report of Checks Issued on a daily basis and copies of validated Deposit Slips summarized in Report on Collections and Deposits to ensure timely recording of disbursements and deposits in the books; and
c. The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer shall analyze the dormant bank account and communicate with the source agency to determine the nature and terms of the account. Reversion to the General Fund may be applied if proven that the unexpended amount is the balance of their counterpart funding to the SEDIP. They shall cause the closure of the dormant account and transfer the balance to an active account in order to protect the amount from possible risk of loss of rights and ownership.
d. For the bank account which was confirmed as closed account but has balance in the FS Schedule of ₱1,000.00, the Municipal Accountant shall analyze the account and/or adjust the amount in their books and the financial statements;
e. The Municipal Accountant shall make the necessary adjusting entries for stale-dated checks over 6 months but not over 2 years to exclude them from the list of outstanding checks, as follows: Cash in Bank - Local Currency, Current Account ₱ XXXXX Accounts Payable ₱ XXXX;
f. The Municipal Treasurer shall send written notice to the payees one month before the check becomes stale, in accordance to Section 104 of GAM for LGUs. The cancelled stale checks shall be reported and attached to the RCI prepared at the period of cancellation.

We recommended that the Management:
a. Require the Local Finance Committee (LFC) to timely and accurately prepare the Local Monthly Reports on Fund Utilization and Status of Implementation of PPAs for BGCM Fund in compliance with Section 4.2 of LBC No. 125;
b. Require the LFC to accomplish the necessary posting in their boards on a regular basis to always keep the public informed and updated on the implementation and utilization of BGCM Fund pursuant to the transparency and full disclosure policy of the government and Section 4.3 of the said circular;
c. Send a written notice and submit all monthly reports for BGCM Fund utilization to the DBM and other government oversight offices where the submission of reports is required under existing laws, rules and regulations, in compliance with Section 4.4 of the said circular;
d. Require the LFC to convene in the determination of PPAs and expenses to be funded from the funds of the LGU in order to properly indicate the specific PPAs and for the timely preparation of supplemental investment programs, budgets & utilization reports and to ensure that disbursements are only made within the limited amounts and nature of the approved PPAs;
e. Direct the LFC to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant concerning the allotment, obligations and disbursements for accurate monthly reporting on fund utilization; and
f. Return to the National Treasury the unutilized balance of the BGCM Fund after the lifting of State of Calamity.

We recommended the following measures:
Requisition of fuel should not be allowed by Management unless the Driver’s Trip Tickets (DTT) are serially numbered, properly and completely filled up and approved;
Designated personnel to process the Monthly Reports of Fuel Consumption and Official Travels should ensure inclusion of all necessary information and make available to the auditor for verification purposes.

Adopt measures to promote and ensure the viability and effective implementation of solid waste management programs in all barangays especially the establishment of MRFs and segregation at source;

Review and update the Municipality’s Ecological Solid Waste Management Plan and prioritize the allocation of funds for the implementation/enforcement of the programs, projects and activities embodied therein pursuant to RA No. 9003; and

Strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 9003 in proper segregation, collection, transport, storage, treatment and disposal of solid waste.

