It is recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

(a) Direct the Municipal Accountant to review thoroughly the documentation of claims for fund transfers. Claims with incomplete documentation should not be processed and should be returned to the requesting unit; 

(b) Require the recipient barangays through the Municipal Accountant to submit liquidation reports for funds received; 

(c.) Require the Municipal Engineer to conduct inspection and to monitor all projects funded by the municipality.

(d) Require the Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary adjusting entries to recognize the transfer of funds as receivable under the account “Due from LGUs”; and 

(e) Adhere strictly to COA Circular No. 2012-001 and other laws, rules and regulations governing disbursements of public funds to protect government funds from possible losses.

Undertake the following steps to account for all existing PPE items in the Municipality:
a) Require each offices/units of the Municipality to conduct their respective inventory-taking, tagging (inventory stickers) and recording of all PPE items present in the offices and the same shall be validated by the Inspectorate Committee and the Supply Unit;
b) Turn-over to the Supply Unit all defective or non-functional PPE items for proper recording and disposal;
c) The Supply Unit shall consolidate all validated inventory reports from the respective offices, together with the respective property numbers for each PPE items, which shall be the basis for preparation of Property Cards and Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
d) The Supply Unit shall prepare the necessary Acknowledgement Receipt (ARE), with corresponding serial numbers, to be issued to the concerned accountable officers/property holders, and shall maintain copies of duly received ARE;
e) The Supply Unit shall furnish the Accounting Unit the electronic and hard copies of the RPCPPE for their reconciliation with the accounting records; and
f) The Accounting Unit shall determine any discrepancies between the RPCPPE and accounting records and prepare the necessary Subsidiary Ledger to record all unaccounted PPE items.
Afterwards, require the heads of the Accounting Unit and Supply Unit to strictly adhere to existing rules and regulations on the maintenance of PPELC and Property Cards and ensure the conduct of the required annual physical count of PPE and timely reconciliation with the Accounting and Supply records against the related PPELC and Property Cards to facilitate timely verification and adjustment of any discrepancies noted.
